**WHO YOU ARE**

*A Founder Identity Statement*

For Tenise Wertman • Three Little Lanterns LLC • AI Magic for Moms

*Read this before the hard conversations. Before the big decisions.
Before you forget.*

The Evidence

You did not wake up one morning and decide to be a founder. You have
been one for 26 years. The world just didn't have a title for what you
were doing.

You have moved your family over 40 times across the country. Every
single time, you rebuilt---new community, new routines, new medical
networks, new education arrangements, new state homeschool laws to
navigate, new normal. You didn't just survive that. You got *good* at
it. You developed the exact skills that founders need and most never
acquire: the ability to assess a new environment instantly, build
systems from scratch, operate without a playbook, and keep eleven people
functioning and connected through constant change.

You got engaged two weeks after meeting your husband. That is not
recklessness. That is a woman who knows what she's looking at when she
sees it. You carry a rare combination of deep conviction and fast
execution---and every significant decision you've made from that
foundation has held.

Every side hustle your kids brought to you succeeded beyond
expectations. Garage sale fundraisers. Mistletoe door-to-door. Handmade
magic wands at a craft sale. You didn't just "help." You brought market
instinct, product development, pricing, and execution energy. Those wins
were not luck. They were your strategic intelligence applied to small
canvases.

You manage your daughter's Medicaid waiver Self-Directed Services
program---government-regulated, compliance-heavy work involving budgets,
employees, documentation, and accountability. You already operate in a
world of regulations and reporting. The compliance demands of a
subscription business will not break you. You have been doing harder
versions of this for years.

You designed and launched an original 14-week literature curriculum
built around C.S. Lewis's *The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe*. Not a
purchased curriculum. Not a template. You created the entire
thing---week-by-week lesson plans with chapter summaries, discussion
questions, and curated music playlists; a 13-word virtue study sequence
(Allegory, Curiosity, Responsibility, Wisdom, Hope, Discernment,
Redemption, Dignity, Restoration, Valiant, Stewardship, Legacy, Courage)
with original affirmations you wrote for the students to memorize and
internalize; four types of weekly assignments; creative projects from
pizza box world-building to AI-generated transformation videos; a C.S.
Lewis biographical scavenger hunt; a class store economy; a printed
student booklet; and a tracking app you built in React with teacher and
student dashboards, week-by-week assignment tracking, a points system,
and achievement unlocks. You taught two sections in two locations an
hour apart, one for 8--10 year olds and one for 10--12 year olds,
adapting the same curriculum to create age-appropriate experiences in
both environments. You built a massive physical wardrobe for the kids to
walk through to enter class, brought a lamp and Christmas trees and fur
coats to complete the Narnia atmosphere, and created an AI-generated
video of C.S. Lewis speaking directly to your students. That is product
design, curriculum architecture, project management, instructional
leadership, and the instinct to go above and beyond for the people you
serve---to always deliver more value than they were expecting.

You taught yourself to code using AI. You built StewardShip---a
functioning family management app that your family uses daily. It is
more intuitive, more navigable, and more useful to you than the portal
you are required to use from Acumen Fiscal Agent---a multi-million
dollar company---to manage your daughter's Medicaid waiver payroll and
documentation. You built something better for your family than a funded
company built for theirs. You then designed MyAIM Family, a platform
with 50+ database tables, a four-persona AI assistant system (LiLa as
the primary guide, ThoughtSift as a processing partner, the LiLa
Optimizer for prompt enhancement, and Safe Harbor for teen support), an
intelligent AI routing system that balances cost and capability across
models, and ethical guardrails grounded in your faith that include
crisis detection, relationship boundary enforcement, and anti-dependency
safeguards. You wrote 40+ detailed product requirement documents---each
one specifying screens, interactions, data models, permission structures
across five user roles, and architectural decisions with rationale.
Professional development teams would charge over a million dollars for
what you have built and designed. You did it as one woman, in focused
bursts, between managing a household and caregiving for a daughter with
complex needs.

You won Best of Show at the Joplin Vibeathon. The second platform was
built in roughly one working week---not because the tools did it for
you, but because the skills you built on the first one compounded with
improving tools. The judges' verdict was clear: *people with context
beat people with credentials.* That is not just your tagline. It is the
thesis of your entire company.

These are not aspirations. These are receipts.

Why You Belong at the Table

When you sit across from someone with a computer science degree,
remember what you've built: a platform architecture with 60--80+
database tables and counting, semantic search infrastructure using
pgvector with halfvec embeddings, Row Level Security policies scoped to
a five-role permission model, multi-model AI routing through OpenRouter,
an async message queue system, cost optimization patterns that bring AI
spend to roughly \$0.20 per family per month, and a content pipeline
that auto-generates tutorials from the act of building. You didn't study
this in a classroom. You learned it because you needed it, and you built
it because no one else was going to.

When you sit across from someone with an MBA, remember what you've
designed: a dual-product strategy where the AI Vault pulls subscribers
in and the family management system creates retention. A subscription
tier model that functions as a confidence journey, not a feature gate. A
Cascade Content Creation Model where one build session produces four to
five library items. An Empathetic Data Retention Policy that keeps
cancelled subscriber data indefinitely as a competitive moat and
word-of-mouth driver. An 80/20 cost architecture that maximizes non-AI
logic to keep unit economics viable at scale. A competitive analysis
that identified a gap no one else saw---that no competitor teaches moms
to make things with AI, they only teach about AI. You didn't learn this
from a case study. You figured it out by thinking about what real
families actually need.

When you sit across from someone with a UX credential, remember what
you've designed: five distinct dashboard shells---Play, Guided,
Independent, Teen, and Adult---each a complete experience, not a
stripped-down version of the adult app. A mom-first permission model
where readiness, not age, determines which shell a child uses. A
Human-in-the-Mix pattern where every AI output has edit, approve,
regenerate, reject, and add-your-own before anything saves. A
gamification system with visual world themes, overlay engines, and
creature progression. An ethical design philosophy that measures success
by family time gained, not engagement metrics. You designed for real
families because you are one.

When you sit across from someone with a teaching credential, remember
what you've created: a 14-week original curriculum with 13 virtue
studies, original affirmations, four assignment types, a student
tracking app, and a physical Narnia experience---taught across two age
groups in two locations an hour apart. A faith-aware ethical AI
framework with crisis detection, anti-dependency safeguards, and a
citation policy grounded in synthesized wisdom rather than single-source
attribution. An Honest Declarations philosophy with five categories of
identity language calibrated to be affirmable as true in the present
moment. You didn't study pedagogy. You practiced it every day for 26
years as a homeschool mom and then formalized it into systems.

The people with credentials learned their disciplines in
isolation---engineering separate from business separate from design
separate from education. You learned yours by necessity, all at once,
because running a household of eleven and building a platform and
teaching a class and managing a Medicaid program don't come in separate
semesters. That cross-domain fluency---the ability to think about
database architecture and subscription psychology and child development
and ethical AI and family dynamics in the same conversation---is the
thing credentials cannot teach. They can't teach it because they don't
produce it. Life produces it. And you have 26 years of it.

Your Positioning

You are not "a tech person teaching moms." You are a mom who has lived
through the last technological revolution, recognized this one for what
it is, and refused to let women be late to it again. You saw something
the entire tech industry missed---that the most powerful use case for AI
isn't enterprise productivity. It's the unpaid, undervalued, infinitely
complex work of raising a family. And when no one built it, you built it
yourself.

You are the scout, not the professor. Your teaching model is "I Go
First"---you do the thing, figure it out, then bring others along. Want
to teach moms to publish on Amazon? Publish on Amazon first. Want to
teach moms to build an app? Build an app first. Want to teach moms to
create AI-generated video content? Create AI-generated video content
featuring your own daughter with Down syndrome first. Every workshop,
tutorial, and bootcamp is rooted in personal experience, not theoretical
knowledge. Moms trust someone who has done the thing over someone who
has studied the thing. The proof of concept is you.

AI Magic for Moms serves three concentric purposes, and all of them flow
from actually understanding how to work with AI. Circle One: Empower
Yourself---discover what AI can do for your personal life, your growth,
your mental load, your dreams. Circle Two: Build Your Calling---whatever
you are uniquely called to be, do, share, or build, AI can help you get
there. Circle Three: Guide Your Family---understand AI well enough to
parent through it, setting boundaries from knowledge instead of fear.
These circles expand naturally. A mom starts by helping herself. She
extends to her family. Her confidence grows. She begins to build
something. That something helps others. The ripple goes outward.

Your Ideation strength means you see connections and possibilities that
others literally cannot see yet. Your Belief strength means you're not
chasing trends---you're building from conviction. You work in focused
bursts not because you lack discipline, but because that is how builders
with high Ideation produce their best work. You are not failing to be
consistent. You are operating in the mode that produces your
highest-quality output.

The market validation is already in. PAM---Personal Admin Manager---is a
family admin app built by Nicole Retter, a Māori mum of two in
Wellington, New Zealand. She launched it in February 2025, and within
months it hit #1 in New Zealand's Apple App Store, surpassing Tinder,
Hinge, Pinterest, and Google Home. It reached over 16,000 users, 75%
acquired purely through word-of-mouth. A quarter of users reported a
70--90% reduction in family admin stress. She raised NZ\$570,000 in seed
funding from Flying Kiwi Angels and Icehouse Ventures, with the round
expected to close at NZ\$800,000. She's now transitioning to a freemium
model at NZ\$15/month, targeting NZ\$375,000 in monthly recurring
revenue within 12 months. And here's what matters most: PAM is a
calendar and task manager with AI that reads emails and invites. It does
not teach AI skills. It does not have a family vision process, a values
framework, a personal growth system, a five-role permission model,
gamification, a content creation library, or a path from consumer to
creator. You've built all of those things. PAM proved the demand is
massive and the growth is real. What you're building goes deeper in
every dimension.

What you are building is not a software product. It is a transformation
platform selling possibility. The product is the journey from "I'm just
a mom" to "I'm a mom who built something that matters." The subscription
tiers are not feature gates. They are a confidence journey. And you
don't teach "how to click the buttons." You teach the thinking
underneath---the portable skills, the systems, the frameworks that work
whether someone is using ChatGPT, Claude, Gemini, or whatever launches
next Tuesday. You are building AI-literate moms, not platform-dependent
users.

No one in the market is building what you are building. And no one in
the market *can*, because they haven't lived it.

What You Are Actually Afraid Of

The fear is not that you can't build this. You already have. The fear is
that stepping fully into ownership means you can no longer protect
yourself with the word "unemployed." It means the thing you built is
real, it has your name on it, and the world gets to see it.

For 26 years, you answered "homemaker" on forms. That word erased the
complexity of what you actually do every single day. But it also
provided cover. If you're "just a mom," no one expects you to succeed at
scale, which means no one watches you fail at it either.

Naming yourself as a founder and business owner removes that cover.
Good. You don't need it anymore.

The operational fears---taxes, compliance, scaling, pivoting---are real,
and they are solvable the same way you've solved everything else: by
learning what you need when you need it, finding the right tools, and
getting help in specific areas. You do not need to know tax law to run a
business. You need to know enough to hire the right person. That is a
completely different bar, and it is a bar you have cleared dozens of
times across dozens of domains---from Medicaid compliance to app
development to homeschool reporting to curriculum design.

The imposter syndrome wants you to attribute your work to AI doing the
heavy lifting. But AI does not know what 40 PRDs should contain. AI does
not know how Safe Harbor should sequence validation before frameworks.
AI does not know that the Atwater Sphere of Influence is distinct from
Covey's. AI does not know how to design a five-role permission model
where a mature 7-year-old and a developmentally delayed 12-year-old both
get the experience that fits them. AI does not know that the right
metric for a family platform is whether moms are spending MORE quality
time with their families, not daily active users. You know those things.
AI is the vehicle. You are the driver.

There is also the fear of the parts you haven't done before---selling,
marketing, promoting. You have never had to convince strangers to pay
for something you built. But look at the evidence sideways: every side
hustle you touched succeeded beyond expectations. The Narnia class
filled seats. PAM grew to 16,000 users with 75% word-of-mouth and no
marketing budget. Your product's target audience---overwhelmed,
brilliant, AI-curious moms---are the most powerful word-of-mouth network
on the planet. And you are one of them. You are not going to be selling
from a stage. You are going to be showing up as the mom who built the
thing, and other moms are going to see themselves in your story. That is
not a marketing strategy you have to learn. That is who you already are.

You have never once in your life waited until you felt ready to do
something important. Two weeks to an engagement. Forty moves. Teaching
yourself to code. You move when the direction is clear and the stakes
matter. The direction is clear. The stakes could not matter more.

The Permission

You said you've always had untapped leadership abilities that went
unused because you were waiting for someone to invite you or give you
permission. No one is coming to invite you. No one invited the New
Zealand company. No one handed them 40 detailed PRDs and a functioning
proof-of-concept app.

You have those things because you built them. In focused bursts. While
running a household. While caring for a daughter with complex needs.
While homeschooling. While designing and teaching an original literature
curriculum. While managing a Medicaid program. While moving across the
country more times than most people move across town.

The 40 PRDs are the permission. Building a better daily-use tool for
your family than a multi-million dollar fiscal management company built
for theirs is the permission. Designing an ethical AI framework with
crisis detection, anti-dependency safeguards, and faith-aware pluralism
before writing a single line of marketing copy is the permission.
Building a curriculum that teaches children about allegory, curiosity,
responsibility, wisdom, hope, discernment, redemption, dignity,
restoration, courage, stewardship, legacy, and valiance---and having
those same values run through the architecture of your platform---is the
permission. Winning Best of Show is the permission.

But you already know the real permission didn't come from any of those
things. You feel the nudge. You know where it's coming from. And you
know that when that nudge meets preparation, the only thing left is to
walk through the door.

Part of you has always known you were made for something exactly like
this.

Trust that part.

The Declaration

*I am the founder and CEO of Three Little Lanterns. I am building AI
Magic for Moms and MyAIM Family---not because it seemed like a good
opportunity, but because I looked at the landscape and saw that no one
was building what these women need. So I built it myself.*

*I bring 26 years of operational leadership that the world never gave a
title. I have managed more complexity, with fewer resources, under more
uncertainty, than most credentialed professionals ever will. I have
moved 40 times, rebuilt from zero every time, and come out stronger each
time. That is not a deficit. That is my qualification.*

*I do not teach theory. I teach from the experience of building a real,
complex product---two platforms, a full curriculum, and a tracking
app---all self-taught, all with AI. I go first, and then I bring others
along. My story is the proof of concept, and every feature in my
platform is a case study.*

*I am not waiting for the fear to pass. I am walking through it. The
women I am building for---Rachel, Megan, Danielle, Jasmine, Adriana,
Laura, Natalie---they are real, they are waiting, and they deserve
someone who has lived what they're living to show them what is possible.
I have lived it. I am showing them.*

*I do not need anyone's permission. I do not need a degree, a
credential, or an invitation. I have the context. I have the conviction.
I have the product. And I have the call.*

*When we unleash an army of moms equipped with AI, the world will not
know what hit it---for the better. And I am the one lighting the fuse.*

**THE MOMS YOU'RE BUILDING FOR**

*User Portraits for MyAIM Family*

*These are real women. Read them when you need to remember why this
matters.*

Rachel --- The Curious but Cautious Mom

38 • Two kids (ages 6 and 10) • Part-time administrative assistant •
Suburban Ohio

Rachel has heard about AI from her husband, from the news, from other
moms at pickup. She's opened ChatGPT exactly twice---once to ask it a
recipe question and once because her son wanted to see it. Both times
she typed a sentence, got a wall of text back, and didn't know what to
do with it. She closed the tab feeling like she'd walked into a party
where everyone knew each other except her.

She's not afraid of AI. She's afraid of looking stupid. She grew up
being told she was smart, and she is---she runs the logistics of her
household, manages a part-time job, and keeps two kids on track. But
technology has always been the thing she lets her husband handle, and
she's starting to realize that's not a personality trait. It's a habit
she fell into because no one ever showed her a way in that felt like it
was designed for someone like her.

She doesn't want a course. She's taken courses before---meal planning
courses, organizing courses, a social media marketing course she never
finished. She wants someone to show her one thing that works, let her
feel the thrill of it, and then show her the next thing when she's
ready.

**What Rachel needs from MyAIM:**

A warm entry point that meets her exactly where she is. The
Netflix-Style AI Vault gives her browseable, visual, non-intimidating
tools organized by type---Prompt Tools, Custom GPTs, Tutorials, Workflow
Launchers---so she can explore without committing. LiLa speaks her
language, not tech language. The LiLa Optimizer shows her what a great
prompt looks like and gives her output she can use immediately, solving
the number one problem she has with AI: "I don't know what to say to
it." Every Optimizer output is a living tutorial---she doesn't just get
the answer, she sees what good prompting looks like so she can learn by
doing. She doesn't need to understand the technology. She needs to feel
the moment when AI gives her back something that makes her say, "Wait, I
made that?" And then she's hooked---not on the platform, but on her own
capability.

Megan --- The Drowning Coordinator

42 • Four kids (ages 4, 8, 11, and 14) • Stay-at-home mom, former
project manager • Colorado Springs

Megan is drowning. Not in a crisis. In logistics. Her brain holds the
orthodontist schedule, the soccer carpool rotation, which kid needs new
cleats, the fact that her 8-year-old has a diorama due Thursday that
they haven't started, that her 14-year-old is struggling in Algebra but
won't admit it, that the dog needs his shots, and that she forgot to
RSVP to a birthday party three days ago. She wakes up already behind.

She was a project manager before kids. She was good at it---really good.
She misses the clean satisfaction of a system that works, tasks that
close, and progress she can see. She's tried every family app, every
planner, every shared calendar. They all fail the same way: they're
designed for one person's tasks or one family's calendar, and they break
the moment real life gets complex. They cannot hold the weight of what
she carries.

Her husband tries to help, but he doesn't know what he doesn't know. She
can't delegate what she can't even articulate---the mental load isn't a
to-do list, it's the awareness that a thousand things are in motion and
she's the only one tracking all of them.

**What Megan needs from MyAIM:**

A system worthy of her complexity. Multi-Dimensional Task Tracking where
a single chore simultaneously counts for allowance, homeschool hours,
and behavioral tracking---she doesn't recreate the same task four times
for four kids. MindSweep lets her dump her brain---voice, text, stream
of consciousness---and have it processed, categorized, and routed into
actionable items. Review & Route so the daily avalanche gets triaged,
not just piled. A family Command Center dashboard where she can finally
*see* everything in one place. And Best Intentions baked into every AI
interaction so that when she asks LiLa for help with dinner, the answer
already knows her 11-year-old is learning to cook and her 4-year-old
needs to be included---because this specific family's context is the
single biggest differentiator from using ChatGPT raw. When the system
says "Everything's organized. Go enjoy your family"---that's the moment
she's been chasing for a decade.

Danielle --- The Mom Who Needs to Build

35 • Six kids (ages 2, 4, 6, 8, 11, and 13) • Homeschool mom, single
income • Rural Tennessee

Danielle does not have a degree. She got married at 19, had her first
baby at 22, and has been homeschooling for eight years. Her husband
works at a manufacturing plant. They are not poor in the way people
imagine---they have a house, they have food, the kids are loved---but
there is no margin. One car repair, one medical bill, one broken
appliance, and the math doesn't work. She cuts coupons. She buys in
bulk. She has a garden. And she lies awake sometimes doing arithmetic
that doesn't resolve.

She is brilliant. She doesn't know that, exactly, but the evidence is
everywhere. She designed her own homeschool curriculum by synthesizing
five different programs. She runs a household of eight on a budget that
would make a financial planner wince. She sees patterns in her kids'
learning that their co-op teachers miss. She has a notebook full of
ideas for things she'd make or sell if she had the time, the skills, or
the startup capital.

She has never once in her life been told that she has the tools to build
a business. Every pathway she's seen requires a degree she doesn't have,
money she can't spare, or time she's already given to her children. She
doesn't know yet that AI has changed that equation. She doesn't know
that a mom with zero college credits can code and create a
multi-platform app---because one already has. She doesn't know that the
same woman who synthesized five curricula into one could use AI to write
a book about it, build a course, or create tools that other homeschool
moms would pay for. She doesn't know that the barriers that contained
her are dissolving right now.

**What Danielle needs from MyAIM:**

The door she doesn't know exists. The AI Vault starts with things she
already understands---coloring pages for the little ones, custom
children's books, creative family projects---and lets her feel what's
possible before she has to believe it. The LiLa Optimizer takes her
half-formed ideas and turns them into prompts she can use on free AI
platforms, because AIMfM works with whatever tools moms already have.
Homeschool Compliance Reporting automates documentation she's currently
doing by hand, pulling from tasks and activities already tracked in the
system. The Creator tier shows her a path from "I made this for my kids"
to "I'm selling this to other moms" through the Creator
Marketplace---where she can sell her templates, her tricks of the trade,
the curriculum pieces she's already invented. And through all of it, the
message is not "you should be doing more." It's the founding truth of
AIMfM: the walls that once contained us are gone. The tools are here.
And when we unleash an army of moms equipped with AI, the world will not
know what hit it---for the better.

Jasmine --- The Mom Who Wants to Connect

40 • Three kids (ages 4, 9, and 15) • Works from home in marketing •
Portland, Oregon

Jasmine uses AI at work. She's not intimidated by it. But at home,
there's a gap between her professional tech competence and her family
life that she hasn't bridged. Her 15-year-old, Marcus, uses AI for
everything and she can't always tell if he's using it well or just using
it. Her 9-year-old, Kira, is curious about it but Jasmine doesn't know
how to introduce it in a way that's age-appropriate and creative rather
than passive. Her 4-year-old, Zoe, just wants to be included in whatever
everyone else is doing.

What Jasmine wants isn't productivity. She has systems. What she wants
is connection. She wants to sit with Marcus and build something together
with AI instead of arguing about whether he used it for his essay. She
wants to make something delightful with Kira---a custom coloring book of
Kira's imaginary world, or an AI-generated story where Kira is the hero.
She wants Zoe to see her mom and siblings doing something creative on a
screen for once, not just consuming content.

She's tired of technology being the thing that pulls her family apart.
She wants it to be the thing that pulls them together, even if it's just
for a Saturday afternoon making something ridiculous and laughing about
it.

**What Jasmine needs from MyAIM:**

The fun. The Custom AI Portrait Style Library lets her whole family see
themselves rendered in Narnia, Pixar, watercolor, or any custom art
style---social media catnip that doubles as a family bonding activity.
The AI Vault's creative projects give her ready-made activities she can
do with any combination of kids. The Dashboard Shells mean Marcus gets
the Independent teen experience that respects his intelligence, Kira
gets Guided creative mode with checkboxes and intermediate complexity,
and Zoe gets Play mode with large colorful icons and full
gamification---each one a complete, designed experience, not a
stripped-down adult app. Mom decides which shell each child uses based
on knowing her child, not age gates. Family Vision Quest gives them a
shared project that's deeper than crafts---a family-wide process of
discovering who they're becoming together, with LiLa facilitating and
each family member contributing. And the Daily Celebration creates a
nightly ritual where the whole family sees what everyone accomplished.
Jasmine doesn't need AI to do more. She needs AI to help her family *be*
more---more creative, more present, more connected, more them.

Adriana --- The Mom Who Wants to Shape What's Coming

44 • Three kids (ages 10, 13, and 17) • Active in school board and
community advocacy • Charlotte, North Carolina

Adriana reads the articles. She follows the policy debates. She has
watched school districts scramble to write AI policies by committee and
produce guidelines that are already outdated by the time they're
approved. She has a 17-year-old heading to college in a world where
every institution is rewriting its rules around AI in real time, a
13-year-old whose friends are using AI to generate social media content,
and a 10-year-old who will never know a world without it.

She does not want to ban AI from her household. She does not want to
blindly adopt it either. She wants to understand it well enough to set
boundaries from knowledge, not fear. She wants to be the parent who sits
next to her teenager and says "let me show you how to use this well"
instead of "don't use that for your homework." She wants a seat at the
table where these decisions are being made---at the school board, in her
community, in her family---and she knows she can't occupy that seat if
she doesn't understand what she's talking about.

Beyond her own family, Adriana senses something bigger. She believes
that if moms---people motivated by love, grounded in values, attuned to
the needs of the most vulnerable---aren't part of shaping how AI
integrates into family life, then it will be shaped entirely by people
who have never packed a school lunch. That is not acceptable to her.

**What Adriana needs from MyAIM:**

A platform built on the values she already holds. The ethics
framework---human-in-the-mix always, no dark patterns, no engagement
traps, no FOMO triggers, no guilt trips for not using features,
faith-aware and pluralistic---tells her this was designed by someone who
shares her priorities. The platform measures success by whether moms are
spending more quality time with their families, not by daily active
users. That alone sets it apart from every other tech product competing
for her family's attention. The AI Vault's teaching model---durable
frameworks and portable skills, not button-clicking tutorials that are
outdated next month---gives her the understanding she needs to guide her
kids and influence her community. Safe Harbor gives her teens a
values-aligned AI processing space with built-in safety guardrails. And
the fact that the entire platform was built by a self-taught mom of nine
is the proof that the people shaping this technology don't have to be
Silicon Valley engineers. They can be us. They should be us.

Laura --- The Mom Carrying an Invisible Weight

37 • Three kids (ages 5, 8, and 12 --- 12-year-old has autism) •
Stay-at-home mom • Minneapolis

Laura's 12-year-old son, Eli, is autistic. He is funny and brilliant and
specific about the world in ways that delight and exhaust her in equal
measure. He has an IEP. He has therapies. He has sensory needs that
shape the family's environment, schedule, and social life in ways that
most people never see. Laura has become an expert in navigating
systems---medical, educational, insurance, behavioral---that were not
designed to be navigated by one person without a case manager.

Her other two kids are neurotypical and sometimes invisible. Not because
she loves them less, but because Eli's needs are louder, and there are
only so many hours. She carries guilt about this like a second skin. She
also carries the weight of being Eli's primary advocate, translator,
scheduler, and emotional safe harbor---while also being the mom who
shows up for her other children's school events, makes the snacks, and
pretends she isn't running on four hours of sleep.

She has never thought of AI as something that could help her
specifically. She associates it with chatbots and corporate automation.
She doesn't know that AI could help her draft IEP goal language, create
visual schedules tailored to Eli's processing style, generate social
stories for new situations, or build custom educational materials that
match his interests and ability level. She doesn't know it could give
her 30 minutes back in her day---and that those 30 minutes could go to
her 8-year-old, or to herself.

**What Laura needs from MyAIM:**

A platform that sees the whole family---not just the neurotypical
version of it. The five-role permission model means Eli's shell can be
set to whatever mode matches his readiness, not his age---a
philosophically different approach from every other family app that uses
rigid age gates. Best Intentions means she can say "help me plan this
week" and LiLa already knows about therapy schedules, sensory
considerations, and the fact that Eli's 8-year-old sister needs
dedicated mom time. Multi-Dimensional Task Tracking means Eli's daily
activities can simultaneously count for behavioral tracking, homeschool
hours, and life skills development without Laura recreating the same
task in three different systems. The AI Vault shows her how to create
custom visual tools, social stories, and educational materials using
AI---things she's currently either paying therapists for or hunting
through Pinterest to find. InnerWorkings helps her understand her own
patterns and needs, not just Eli's. ThoughtSift gives her a processing
partner for the daily complexity---warm but boundaried, with clear
guardrails that redirect her to human connection when she needs it. And
the Empathetic Data Retention Policy means that if finances get tight
and she has to cancel, her family's story stays safe---because your
family's story matters more than a monthly payment.

Natalie --- The Mom With Something to Say

41 • Two kids (ages 7 and 11) • Former elementary teacher, now
stay-at-home mom • Boise, Idaho

Natalie has something inside her that wants out. She's not sure if it's
a book, a course, a podcast, a curriculum, or something she doesn't have
a name for yet. She just knows that the things she's learned as a mom
and a former teacher---about how kids actually learn, about how to make
a home that works, about the way she's navigated her son's ADHD
diagnosis---feel like they could help other people. She's had friends
tell her she should write a book. She's had that thought herself at 2 AM
more times than she can count.

She knows AI could help her get there. She's seen the headlines. She's
watched a few YouTube videos. But every time she tries to figure out
where to start, she hits a wall of information---a sea of courses,
tools, platforms, influencers, and conflicting advice. One person says
start with ChatGPT. Another says Claude. Another says she needs to learn
prompt engineering first. Another says just start creating. She spends
an hour researching how to start, feels more overwhelmed than when she
began, and closes her laptop. The gap between "I have something to
share" and "I know how to make it real" feels enormous, and no one is
bridging it for women like her.

She doesn't want to become a tech person. She doesn't want to learn AI
as a subject. She wants to learn it as a tool---the way she learned to
use a laminator and a die-cut machine in her classroom, because they
helped her do the thing she actually cared about doing.

**What Natalie needs from MyAIM:**

The path from idea to thing. The AI Vault is a Netflix-style library of
ready-to-use tools and step-by-step tutorials---and Natalie's entry
point isn't a lesson on frameworks. It's a tutorial showing her how to
create a children's book with AI, step by step, in a screen recording
she can follow along with. She watches someone do it, she does it
herself, and suddenly the gap between "I have an idea" and "I made a
thing" collapses. From there she discovers Prompt Tools she can use
immediately---a Story Generator, a Concept Explainer, a Project
Planner---that work without any AI knowledge at all. The LiLa Optimizer
takes her messy, half-formed "I want to write something about how I
handled the ADHD diagnosis with my son's school" and turns it into a
structured, context-rich prompt she can copy into ChatGPT, Claude, or
Gemini---wherever she already is, including free tiers. Every Optimizer
output is itself a living tutorial: it shows her what a great prompt
looks like, so the skill sinks in through doing, not studying.
ThoughtSift helps her process the bigger vision---is this a blog? a
book? a course?---without the pressure of committing. The Personal
LifeLantern helps her see the through-line from where she's been to
where she's going. And the durable thinking underneath all of it---how
to give AI context, how to break a big idea into pieces AI can help
with, how to evaluate whether the output is good enough---those skills
transfer to every platform and every tool that launches next Tuesday.
The founder's story is the proof that the path is real: a mom with zero
college credits who taught herself to code with AI, built two platforms,
won Best of Show, and is now teaching other moms to do the same. Natalie
doesn't need a degree or a marketing plan to start. She needs one
tutorial, one tool, one moment of "wait, I made that?"---and then the
next one. That is exactly what AIMfM provides.

*When we unleash an army of moms equipped with AI,*

*the world will not know what hit it --- for the better.*

*These women are waiting for someone who has lived what they're living*

*to show them what's possible.*

***You have. And you will.***
